                                <condition>A large irregularly shaped cave divided into two aisles by a rock buttress. The walls of the cave are full of natural fissures but the south aisle of the cave also exhibits copious carvings and graffiti, including two ogham inscriptions. In addition to the carvings and inscriptions, there are opposing rows of small holes cut into the rock about 1 1/2-2m above the present floor. These have been interpreted as sockets for small bars of wood (Forsyth 1996, 94). </condition>
                            </supportDesc>
                            <layoutDesc>
                                <layout>The south aisle of the cave is decorated with carvings of horses, deer, and concentric circles. The buttress bears a large and a small cross and the figure of a man with raised hands holding a curved object above his head. Towards the entrance, on the south wall there are two triangles and on the north wall of the south aisle there is a group of serpent-like spirals and two ogham inscriptions (Forsyth 1996, 94-5). The inscriptions are carved on the left-hand wall of the cave, about <height unit="m">2m</height> above the present floor. The area is also decorated with a panel of snake-like, loose spiral interlace graffiti (Forsyth 1996, 94-5). The first inscription (S-BUT-001) is about <dim type="depth" unit="m">9m</dim> from the entrance gate. To the left of the first inscription, Forsyth also observed what appears <q>to be further ogham-like marking</q> (S-BUT-X01), however, these may <q>be natural fissures in the rock face with only a coincidental resemblance to ogham</q> (Forsyth 1996, 95). There is a second inscription (S-BUT-002) about <dim type="depth" unit="m">11m</dim> from the entrance gate. Located 1.6m to the right of the first inscription (S-BUT-001) and parallel with it, there appears to be another ogham text (S-BUT-003) which is about 300mm in length and extends to the underside of an oblique overhang. </layout>
                            </layoutDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <handDesc>
                            <handNote>The inscription is <q>not cut into the rock but seems to be scribed in pencil or some kind of ink</q> (Jacskon 1973, 95). Jackson attributes this pigment-based ogham inscription to a <q>recent vandal</q> (1973, 95). Fisher described the inscription as artificial <q>but several of the horizontal lines which abut or span it are probably natural cracks</q> (2001, 66). <!--<height></height>-->
                            </handNote>
                        </handDesc>
                    </physDesc>
