                        <provenance type="found" when="1973">Located in a sandstone cliff about 3km north of <placeName type="townland">Blackwaterfoot</placeName> are a series of caves of which the King's Cave at <placeName type="townland">Drumadoon (<foreign xml:lang="sga">Druim an DÃºin</foreign> 'ridge of the fort')</placeName> is the largest. The walls of the cave exhibit carvings which span from perhaps the Bronze Age to the present day. The animal and geometric carvings have been known since at least the end of the seventeenth century, but the presence of ogham was not noticed until about <date>1968</date> (Forsyth 1996, 94). Jackson documented the first inscription Blackwaterfoot (S-BUT-001) and mentioned this pigment ogham text Blackwaterfoot 3 (S-BUT-003) in <date>1973</date>. The second ogham inscription, Blackwaterfoot 2 (S-BUT-002), was not discovered until <date>1992</date> when Ian Fisher of the RCAHMS conducted further survey work on the cave (ibid.).
                        </provenance>
